  "prompt": "What is the best way to remove permanent marker from a countertop?",
  "response": "Removing permanent marker from a countertop can be tricky, but there are several methods you can try:\n\n1. **Rubbing Alcohol:** Apply a small amount of rubbing alcohol to a cotton ball or cloth and gently rub the marker stain. Alcohol is effective at dissolving ink.\n\n2. **Baking Soda and Water:** Make a paste using baking soda and water. Apply the paste to the stain and gently scrub with a sponge or cloth.\n\n3. **Acetone (Nail Polish Remover):** Use a small amount of acetone on a cloth and rub the stain. Be cautious, as acetone can damage some countertop materials.\n\n4. **Magic Eraser:** These cleaning pads are designed to remove difficult stains, including permanent marker. Dampen the Magic Eraser with water and gently scrub the stained area.\n\n5. **Toothpaste:** Use non-gel toothpaste and a toothbrush to scrub the stain. The mild abrasives in the toothpaste can help lift the ink.\n\n6. **Hydrogen Peroxide:** Apply hydrogen peroxide to a cloth and gently rub the stain. This method is safer for delicate surfaces.\n\n7. **WD-40:** Spray a small amount of WD-40 on the stain and wipe it off with a cloth. Rinse the area afterward to remove any residue.\n\nAlways test a small, inconspicuous area of the countertop first to ensure the cleaning method doesn\u2019t cause any damage or discoloration. Rinse the area thoroughly after cleaning to remove any residual cleaning agents.",
